article.description: Swin Cash had 20 points and 10 rebounds as the Detroit Shock snapped a 17-game road losing streak with a 74-66 victory over the Charlotte Sting on Saturday night.
article.headline: Shock snap 17-game losing streak
article.linkText: Cash is money as Shock snap losing skid in Charlotte
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Swin Cash had 20 points and 10 rebounds
as the Detroit Shock snapped a 17-game road losing streak with a
74-66 victory over the Charlotte Sting on Saturday night.

	   Elaine Powell added 18 points, and Deanna Nolan had 15 for the
Shock (6-18), who were winless on the road since beating Portland
on July 24, 2001.

	   Detroit is 6-8 since former Pistons player Bill Laimbeer
replaced Greg Williams as head coach. The Shock opened the season
0-13 and lost 16 of their first 17 games.

	   Detroit avoided tying Phoenix for the longest road losing streak
in league history. Phoenix lost its 18th consecutive road game
Friday night at Utah.

	   "We talked about the streak before the game,'' Laimbeer said.
"We talked about how Phoenix held the record and we wanted no part
of it. We play so hard that we deserve the wins we're getting.''

	   Andrea Stinson scored 17 points, and Allison Feaster added 13
for the Sting (14-11), who have dropped consecutive home games
after winning 10 of their first 12.

	   "I'm frustrated because I see our potential and I have a vision
of where we should be right now,'' Sting coach Anne Donovan said.
"We're not performing at our potential.''

	   Detroit outrebounded Charlotte 38-25 and held the Sting to
35-percent shooting.

	   "We are building for the future,'' Cash said. "We're a fun
team to watch and I think we are making some noise in the East.''

	   Charlotte used an 11-0 run to take a 54-52 lead, ending on Kelly
Miller's steal and layup with 8:17 to go. Detroit answered with
seven straight points to regain control.

	   The Sting got as close as three at 67-64 on Stinson's 3-pointer
with 1:01 to play, but the Shock went 7-for-8 at the free-throw
line to put the game away.

	   The loss dropped Charlotte to third place in the Eastern
Conference, one game behind first-place Washington and a half-game
back of New York.

	   "We're not rebounding and we're not getting it done on the
defensive end,'' Stinson said. "We have to start over and figure
out how to get it done.''
